I&#x27;ve seen this example several times now, and I never got why it was so bad: it&#x27;s mostly an objection to the namespace qualification syntax if anything. It would actually be written:<p><pre><code>    use std::ops::Neg;
    struct Foo<&#x27;a,P> where P: Neg + &#x27;a, <P::Neg>::Output: &#x27;a {
        foo: &&#x27;a Bar<P>,
    }
</code></pre>
And with further proposed improvements it would be:<p><pre><code>    use std::ops::Neg;
    struct Foo<&#x27;a,P> where P: Neg + &#x27;a, P::Output: &#x27;a {
        foo: &&#x27;a Bar<P>,
    }
</code></pre>
Not bad. It&#x27;s saying &quot;I have a generic structure over a type parameter P tied to a lifetime &#x27;a, and P must overload the unary minus operator&quot;.
